WEBVTT

00:00.391 --> 00:05.693
Hello everyone, welcome back to another episode of the Grand Prixquel podcast where we discuss all things Feeder Series.

00:06.134 --> 00:11.456
On today's episode, we are going to be doing a review of the British F4 and Italian F4 weekends.

00:12.176 --> 00:16.378
Your hosts today are myself, Robin, Alex, Peter, and Niamh.

00:21.560 --> 00:23.361
So um, Italian F4.

00:23.901 --> 00:25.562
When I say I have-

00:27.080 --> 00:33.103
Everyone who knows me, anyone who's talked to me before, knows how I feel about the 2025 Italian F4 season, right?

00:33.623 --> 00:38.785
But I swear to God, I have not seen a stinker this bad from R-ace before.

00:39.385 --> 00:44.348
Like, just, okay, pace-wise, they were fine, right?

00:45.308 --> 00:52.072
But then Craigie qualified like P6 and Consani qualified P4 for the first race.

00:52.593 --> 00:54.354
And like everything was fine, right?

00:54.774 --> 00:59.557
But then the race starts and Craigie pushes Consani off track.

01:00.198 --> 01:05.941
I think it was probably a racing incident because Craigie didn't get a penalty for it.

01:06.422 --> 01:09.864
He just thought he was Pierre Gasly in Qatar 2021.

01:09.944 --> 01:14.507
I mean, disasterclass, good in qualifying and in the race, he just-

01:15.187 --> 01:26.109
And like Kenzo went on to crash into Savinkov as well, which actually did get him a penalty, a four-place grid penalty for the next race.

01:26.830 --> 01:34.971
Andy got a penalty, his first penalty was also four places for the next race, because he turned on his engine before the one-minute board.

01:35.331 --> 01:38.432
And this penalty, there were- So many drivers got this penalty.

01:38.772 --> 01:45.437
I don't know why, because you had Consani, you had Maccagnani who lost the win because of it.

01:45.878 --> 01:48.440
And many other drivers, I don't remember names.

01:49.120 --> 01:52.603
And it's like, do the drivers know they're not supposed to do that?

01:53.263 --> 01:55.685
I think it's just a classic F4 race.

01:55.945 --> 01:59.068
I mean, it's always the most random stuff going on.

01:59.748 --> 02:01.490
You know, anything's gonna happen.

02:02.150 --> 02:03.631
It happened all weekend.

02:04.391 --> 02:06.933
Is there any chance that the rule changed recently?

02:07.333 --> 02:08.373
It's possible, yeah.

02:08.413 --> 02:18.459
Because I know obviously there's been a lot of confusion over in Indycar about changing rules regarding push-to-pass with them, but if something like this has happened it could just be that the drivers keep forgetting.

02:18.942 --> 02:21.362
It is possible, yeah, they changed the rule.

02:21.803 --> 02:27.504
I remember like with F3, Enzo Deligny, like airing everyone, not knowing the FIA test thingy.

02:28.104 --> 02:29.484
It's probably just like that.

02:29.504 --> 02:32.664
It's like nobody knew the answers to that.

02:32.724 --> 02:37.085
It's probably the same thing, they’re just a bit not fully aware of things.

02:37.365 --> 02:39.006
I really want to do that FIA test.

02:39.026 --> 02:41.886
Like it's completely unrelated, but I really want to do it.

02:41.906 --> 02:45.167
I just want to know what, like, what will I do on it?

02:45.647 --> 02:46.907
That's where we'd pass it.

02:47.288 --> 02:47.968
I think we would.

02:47.988 --> 02:49.889
Yeah, we're better than those drivers.

02:50.541 --> 02:52.658
Grand Prixquel podcast racing team.

02:51.309 --> 02:58.452
One of my friends had to do something like it for marshalling, and then she had to do a bunch of other thingies for her actual karting.

02:58.832 --> 03:00.813
And she was like, oh, this is so much fun.

03:00.873 --> 03:02.334
I actually know the answers to this.

03:02.414 --> 03:03.194
And I was like, oh.

03:03.734 --> 03:05.135
And she was like, yeah, there was someone that failed it.

03:05.155 --> 03:06.035
And I'm like, what?

03:06.972 --> 03:08.214
Anyways, we need to get back.

03:09.175 --> 03:14.421
The thing is, I have not seen this penalty happen before, in like other F4 series.

03:14.461 --> 03:22.411
Like even if you look at, like UAE4, which just happened over the winter, that's not something that's like affected drivers before.

03:22.431 --> 03:24.233
So maybe it is just a rule change.

03:25.248 --> 03:39.880
yeah but it could also be just the amount of drivers that we have here, it's just like there's a higher likelihood that this will happen and because, also considering how you know big the grid is, that drivers think hey

03:40.741 --> 03:42.403
We could start any second now.

03:42.503 --> 03:49.652
I should, you know, do this now because especially if you're, like, further in the back and you think, hey, maybe I should do it now.

03:50.033 --> 03:53.357
I think it's something that will be resolved in the next race.

03:53.417 --> 03:55.760
But sometimes these things just happen.

03:56.483 --> 03:58.885
Thing is, these are experienced drivers.

03:58.985 --> 04:01.166
Consani obviously had most of it-

04:01.907 --> 04:03.648
He's in his second year of F4.

04:03.908 --> 04:07.090
He did a lot of Italian F4 last season and also French F4.

04:07.150 --> 04:08.151
We've talked about this before.

04:08.471 --> 04:14.815
Maccagnani has done F4 Southeast Asia, Formula Trophy, UAE4 and is now doing Italian F4 as well.

04:15.135 --> 04:17.497
These guys have experience.

04:18.123 --> 04:35.198
Maybe they're stressed, maybe they're just a bit, you know, now it's the real main campaign they have to deliver, and especially because they're all teens, I can totally imagine that there's also just a bit of stress, a bit of, wait, how do I actually, you know, proceed here?

04:36.318 --> 04:41.063
It might also be that they're just coming down on it more from a safety perspective.

04:41.723 --> 04:53.414
I don't know if anything happened that could have triggered it, like say, you know, oh, it was happening before but we didn't really care because it wasn't affecting anything, then something happens and they're like, actually no, we need to stop them.

04:54.215 --> 04:55.096
If someone's gonna get hurt.

04:55.687 --> 04:56.888
Yeah, that's possible as well.

04:57.048 --> 04:58.629
Anyways, I have no clue.

04:59.370 --> 05:00.851
But back to R-ace.

05:01.151 --> 05:11.920
So Andy already has a four-place grid penalty for the next race, and he causes a collision with Edu Robinson, which I think that's where he had to DNF the first race.

05:12.721 --> 05:14.943
And so he got a two-place grid penalty for that as well.

05:16.043 --> 05:27.610
Payton Westcott got a two-place grid penalty for overtaking under safety car, and Tamas Gender got his best lap time during qualifying deleted for causing a red flag.

05:27.911 --> 05:34.515
So really the only driver in the entire lineup that didn't get a penalty over the weekend is Emily, because she's the GOAT.

05:35.455 --> 05:37.756
Did they just have a competition here?

05:37.796 --> 05:39.717
Who could get the most penalties?

05:39.797 --> 05:41.398
Maybe. It’s sounding like that.

05:41.938 --> 05:47.481
It seems it could have bet like... How are all of them getting penalized for something? This is like-

05:48.001 --> 05:52.543
They saw that the car was fast and they wanted to make me suffer anyways.

05:53.504 --> 05:55.685
You gotta give the others a chance too, you know?

05:56.365 --> 06:00.287
Let them get ahead of you and then you go in and just destroy them.

06:00.587 --> 06:01.888
We gotta stay positive here.

06:02.648 --> 06:11.730
Yeah, so I was kind of scared that Andy and Kenzo would not qualify for race 4, because they both, like, DNF'd the first race.

06:13.251 --> 06:15.771
But they both qualified, so it was fine.

06:17.552 --> 06:21.492
Race 1, Emily scored points in race 1, which was really nice.

06:22.173 --> 06:31.855
She did finish the race in P16, but then someone in the front got a penalty, so she got promoted to P15, which big fan of the points down to P15.

06:33.056 --> 06:38.180
I really like it because often you see that it can be dominated by a few teams.

06:38.861 --> 06:42.484
It really gives the smaller teams and all drivers more of a chance to score points.

06:43.644 --> 06:58.676
I think also, it's really great that we have points to P15 and I think we could go even further down because it does make a huge difference if a driver finishes in like P30 or P15 because there's worlds between it.

06:59.076 --> 07:11.066
And as Peter just, you know, started to say, we have so many drivers in Prema, US Racing, you know, these big teams where it's pretty much clear that you will score points.

07:11.967 --> 07:29.942
and if all the points scoring positions are already filled with these drivers for smaller teams there's just no chance at all to get points, but now we see it more drivers from more smaller teams also get the chance and still I think we could go even further down with the points just to make it really clear because

07:30.923 --> 07:32.885
For the championship, it won't really matter.

07:33.405 --> 07:48.938
But if you're a driver that, you know, does not have the big money to go to Prema or US Racing, it does make a difference if you, you know, finish every single race in the top 20 while your teammates are only in the 30s.

07:49.722 --> 07:50.863
Yeah, I completely agree.

07:50.903 --> 08:02.612
I also think there's a big difference like when it comes to the end of the season, because obviously if it's only points up to P10 and you were consistently finishing 11th, you're getting zero points, so you're going to be way further down.

08:02.973 --> 08:07.096
But if you're now getting points up to P15, then you're going to be a lot higher up.

08:07.136 --> 08:13.921
It gives you a more accurate idea of what the actual, like, results were like, as opposed to, oh, this person got a random win.

08:13.961 --> 08:14.562
So now they're

08:14.962 --> 08:18.703
Seventh when actually they should be like realistically they should have been about 17th.

08:19.423 --> 08:25.944
Especially given how many drivers are coming with Prema, US and R-ace will eventually be up there.

08:26.644 --> 08:30.225
They will essentially dominate the top 10 for most of the season.

08:30.845 --> 08:36.886
So really this gives everyone else more of a chance to show like, hey, are they able to consistently be in the top 15?

08:37.126 --> 08:41.967
Because, like you said, actually it's a big difference between being P14 and being P28.

08:43.317 --> 08:49.739
Yeah, I mean, for many drivers like want to make it to F1, is still not enough or anything.

08:50.199 --> 09:01.581
But if you're a small driver from a smaller team, making these points and being able to say, hey, in a field of like 50 drivers, I was able to score points.

09:01.642 --> 09:03.702
I was still top 15.

09:03.742 --> 09:07.523
It's really good, you know, really good way to market themself also.

09:08.005 --> 09:11.610
And I thought it was really nice seeing the girls fighting for points positions.

09:11.650 --> 09:16.978
I mean, we saw Emily up in like P13 at some point, but then she dropped down a bit.

09:17.479 --> 09:19.562
Still ended up scoring a point in P15.

09:20.623 --> 09:23.627
Emma scored a point in, was it race 3?

09:24.672 --> 09:36.401
Can we talk about Emma, please? Because in Race 1, Emma ran as high as P10 in parts, but then she had to pit for tyres, because I think it was that she had, she had some problems with the tyres.

09:36.641 --> 09:37.942
She had a puncture, yeah.

09:38.323 --> 09:47.109
Yeah, the point is she was P10 at points, she overtook, she was really really good, and I think it was a great showing from her, and I think it really proves

09:48.177 --> 10:06.084
I was really really surprised by her because she was with PHM and it's generally an alright team but like not a team expect them to win or anything but to show that she can fight to be in the top 10 is great showing and I think we will see more good showings from her.

10:06.824 --> 10:15.149
Also, Rafaela Ferreira, who also raced in Italian F4 this weekend, ran in the top 15 for a while in race one.

10:15.589 --> 10:22.873
But right in like the last two or three laps, she dropped down from, I think she was like P12 at some point, but she dropped down.

10:23.474 --> 10:31.378
She was aided in the fact that Emma went into the pits while she was, you know, in front of her on the track.

10:31.838 --> 10:33.780
So she got a few of those positions.

10:34.892 --> 10:47.987
you know because other drivers had problems but generally it was alright but I don't quite know why she dropped down it was not mentioned on the stream or anywhere but I could imagine maybe she overused the tires

10:48.645 --> 10:55.468
And like, even if they weren't scoring points, Payton Westcott, for example, finished P16 in race two.

10:55.989 --> 10:58.270
And like, it's nice to see them fighting up there.

10:58.690 --> 11:05.413
And I feel like for Emily, for example, I mentioned this in like, on Twitter.

11:05.774 --> 11:14.378
The qualifying groups were like, really unbalanced and Emily like, mentioned it in her Instagram post after the races.

11:15.058 --> 11:17.640
The qualifying groups were really unbalanced and

11:18.720 --> 11:25.911
It just really screwed Emily over and I feel like she could have qualified higher if the groups were a bit more balanced.

11:27.053 --> 11:33.162
Yeah, I think we'll see that improve in, like, the next few weekends when the groups will be normal.

11:34.717 --> 11:42.143
Yeah I think overall I think it's really positive and I'm pretty excited for like you know the upcoming weekends.

11:43.264 --> 11:45.886
I think we should get into the individual races now.

11:46.946 --> 12:01.578
So in race one we had, initially we had Maccagnani win on track but then he got a 10 second penalty so Aksoy inherited the win. I mean, Aksoy did start on pole but he had a bit of a poor start,

12:02.158 --> 12:09.203
falling down, I think he fell to, around p3, p4, but then end of the first lap he recovered back to p2 on track.

12:10.924 --> 12:22.433
I mean it is quite a good, I mean it is a shame he lost the lead at the start, I think he had the pace to keep the lead, but overall it was a very Prema and US dominated top 10.

12:23.214 --> 12:27.717
Bondarev made it into P3 on track P2 in the end.

12:28.138 --> 12:35.704
He really underperformed this week I feel, like, because he went into this very much being the favourite for the title.

12:36.384 --> 12:39.585
Is he not also doing his third year of Italian F4 now?

12:40.305 --> 12:45.686
I mean, second full year, third, because he only really did the last two rounds or something in 2020.

12:45.746 --> 12:47.487
Okay, I can't remember.

12:47.747 --> 12:50.727
So he's, like really experienced compared to some of the others.

12:51.508 --> 12:59.249
Especially, I mean, essentially getting outperformed by Aksoy and Maccagnani who are both rookies as well.

12:59.429 --> 13:01.930
He was behind Cosma in one of the races, wasn't he?

13:02.350 --> 13:08.275
Yeah, in Race 2 he was, and I mean, even in Race 4, they were around the same pace.

13:09.075 --> 13:20.144
And I think Costoya, I mean, Costoya just had a really poor qualifying, he qualified in around P25, but he made up a lot of positions, about 10 positions in all his races.

13:20.924 --> 13:29.771
So, I mean, it's really not a good look to being outperformed by two of your rookie teammates, nearly three of your rookie teammates at first.

13:30.412 --> 13:35.582
Technically Maccagnani isn't a rookie though, cause he did a F4 Southeast Asia last season.

13:36.480 --> 13:41.663
But I did say Aksoy as well, Aksoy did Formula Trophy, but they're rookies to Italian, I mean.

13:41.723 --> 13:59.952
But also, experience-wise, Bondarev is known to, you know, he should also be known to fighting in the front with a great team in Italian F4 with Prema, and he should have the experience in, what we usually say, it's difficult to...

14:01.073 --> 14:18.065
You know, getting through the vibe of it all because it is different when you have 30 cars on track, especially for guys like Cristofor, who then come from the back and have to do a lot of overtakes on slower cars on cars with drivers that maybe do drive a bit erratically.

14:18.566 --> 14:20.287
He should perform more.

14:21.469 --> 14:25.851
I mean, I think it is just a week when he struggled in general, but so I guess.

14:26.591 --> 14:30.213
We'd very much have to wait till the next round to make a proper full judgement.

14:30.773 --> 14:39.637
But I mean, also, shout out again to Emily Cotty, P15, and how did P15 after penalties, so it's always nice to see her in the point.

14:40.317 --> 14:47.803
For me race 1 was kind of horrible because you know again it's the whole thing with R race but um we move on.

14:49.064 --> 14:52.607
Race 2 again Aksoy, with the poor start.

14:53.287 --> 14:57.350
Started in P2 and felt P4.

14:58.071 --> 15:00.433
I think that is him showing his inexperience.

15:01.243 --> 15:05.585
But that's something he can definitely improve on.

15:05.945 --> 15:07.446
We saw it in Race 4 though.

15:08.086 --> 15:09.627
Race 4, he kept the lead.

15:10.007 --> 15:21.353
And he was really lucky to be able to get up there again and not lose so many points and positions, as that he would drop down somewhere where he couldn't recover from.

15:22.037 --> 15:28.745
Yeah, so we had Luka Sammalisto winning it from Pole, David Cosma in second and Aksoy in third.

15:29.045 --> 15:40.919
The thing is about Luka Sammalisto is that I was not expecting him up there because I remember last season he was P8 in the championship between Oliveri and Powell and it's like

15:41.915 --> 15:44.457
You were P8 last year, what are you, what are you doing?

15:44.477 --> 15:57.987
I think it’s just him– maybe he's just jealous with his tracks a lot of the time, he could just be a driver, just, you know, you have a good qualifying and he’s just on it the whole weekend, I think it is partly that as well, I mean.

15:58.467 --> 16:01.169
He's at US Racing now?

16:01.970 --> 16:04.872
He was at US Racing last season too.

16:05.571 --> 16:12.514
But I feel like, I don't know, this race, Weekend, definitely, US Racing was really, really on pace.

16:12.534 --> 16:19.236
And we also saw it with Bansal and Kraling, who both got really, really good points this weekend.

16:19.256 --> 16:25.519
So I think, you know, he's also the one in the team that has, I think he has the most experience in US Racing.

16:25.539 --> 16:27.920
So he's kind of- Yeah, it's his third season of F4.

16:27.940 --> 16:32.942
I mean, he's kind of taking the lead that we expected Bondarev to do at Prema.

16:33.601 --> 16:34.642
Very much so.

16:34.942 --> 16:38.203
Because, again, Bondarev was the third Prema in this race.

16:38.903 --> 16:43.705
And also, I want to say, Kenzo Craigie, I think he fell to around P30 at the start.

16:43.745 --> 16:44.065
I don't know.

16:44.225 --> 16:45.706
He stalled at the start.

16:46.206 --> 16:50.808
Yeah, he stalled at the start, because I saw him a lot, and then he still made it up into P13 in the end.

16:51.088 --> 16:52.949
So he really shows his pace, I think.

16:53.249 --> 17:00.392
And as long as he has a tidy weekend where, I mean, if he started in P6 like he had qualified around there,

17:01.112 --> 17:04.914
I think he could have gotten onto the podium maybe or gotten a solid top five.

17:05.174 --> 17:06.415
So that is hope for him.

17:06.435 --> 17:08.956
He has a clean weekend is what he needs.

17:09.476 --> 17:16.700
Yeah, I think the pace that the R-ace drivers have shown this weekend with the overtakes has been really positive.

17:17.160 --> 17:19.882
And yeah, it wasn't a great weekend overall.

17:20.282 --> 17:29.386
But like I said earlier, I think we should improve over the rest of the season and hopefully we'll have the drivers fighting for wins.

17:29.907 --> 17:30.387
Hopefully.

17:31.330 --> 17:35.596
Yeah, and I think part of it for him, for Craigie, is also just inexperience.

17:36.217 --> 17:38.400
He's still getting used to things, so...

17:38.820 --> 17:39.982
It's all a learning thing.

17:40.022 --> 17:43.707
That is what F4 is for, is to learn how to race in cars.

17:44.208 --> 17:44.809
End of the day.

17:45.305 --> 17:56.047
Yeah, but also Italian F4 is a fairly long, you know, championship and there is a lot of races and the R-ace drivers are generally usually expected.

17:56.227 --> 18:03.069
–If we have this full race weekend format– to also be in the fourth race generally.

18:03.129 --> 18:07.790
So I think there is a great opportunity to improve for everyone.

18:08.877 --> 18:16.643
Race 3, we had Maccagnani winning, Cosma in second, David Walther in the Maffi racing in third, I mean.

18:17.064 --> 18:20.046
What is a Maffi racing car doing on the podium?

18:20.326 --> 18:21.227
What is going on?

18:21.327 --> 18:22.468
What is this championship?

18:23.569 --> 18:28.533
I mean, I do feel a bit bad for Samalisto, he just kind of, his car just kind of died.

18:29.614 --> 18:32.937
P4 in a Maffi car is also incredible.

18:33.952 --> 18:36.897
It kind of come out of nowhere because I think-.

18:37.298 --> 18:39.742
He's just one of those names who are just kind of there.

18:40.483 --> 18:45.191
Like I was already surprised during qualifying because I think he qualified like P7 or something?

18:45.988 --> 19:14.417
I just wanted to mention after the first qualifying I did a rough order of like the pecking order of the teams and I had Maffi racing genuinely as the weakest team although they only have two drivers so it's hard to rate but I- after the last scene, I did not expect them to even get points so I think David Walther is one of those guys who I think he showed incredibly this weekend and he will have you know

19:15.377 --> 19:22.921
put this in his resume somewhere, he will have gotten, you know, the attention that he would not usually get.

19:22.941 --> 19:41.429
And I think it will be quite interesting to watch him maybe be able, even if he does not get into the title fight, if he gets good points, I think it could really be a total underdog story with more sponsors also coming his way.

19:41.449 --> 19:42.710
It's great.

19:43.171 --> 19:49.403
They won't say Costoya again had a good recovery, but then I don't know what happened to him, but actually coming to the line.

19:49.423 --> 19:52.889
He got crashed into by Rodriguez, I think it was.

19:54.079 --> 19:58.563
But it's really simple, again he started in the mid 20s and he made it up to P11.

19:58.623 --> 20:18.198
See I mean it really makes me wonder if he’s a good qualifier and what can he do because you know from karting how good he is and I think I've been a bit surprised at the performance of the other Premas because going into this, we very much, at least are very much expected Bondarev to be the lead Prema and probably Costoya as the second best.

20:18.779 --> 20:22.862
But seeing the others: Cosma, Maccagnani up there was a bit of a surprise.

20:23.953 --> 20:39.936
I've said it, I said it, that I think Aksoy will surprise, and I did not expect him to instantly win, I did expect him to at least get a few podiums, so I'm not as surprised by him, and Maccagnani has the support by Ferrari, no?

20:40.336 --> 20:52.378
Yeah, he does, about the Cosma as well being up, by the fact that all of them are outperforming Bondarev,also Costoya, who very much were the two that people would expect to be the lead Premas, it's more that.

20:53.063 --> 20:56.205
I thought Costoya crossing the line backwards was really funny though.

20:56.825 --> 21:12.155
But I think it's a mix of anyways, like the Prema drivers on Maccagnani, Aksoy and Cosma, just being better than we expected and Bondarev being, I'm sorry but he's worse than we expected.

21:13.182 --> 21:16.284
I think race four is a bit of a struggle for me. Aksoy-

21:16.904 --> 21:23.447
Actually, I mean, Race Four, I mean, I just want to say, thankfully, everybody's okay after that big crash at the start.

21:23.467 --> 21:26.849
But if we had, I think, Bearman stalled, somebody went to the back of him.

21:27.469 --> 21:28.790
It's a bit of, I mean, we saw the wheel.

21:28.810 --> 21:30.411
It all kind of bent out of shape.

21:30.911 --> 21:34.052
I was impressed at how perfectly up works at point.

21:34.673 --> 21:37.514
How do you even get it that perfectly upward, eh?

21:37.863 --> 21:43.785
He posted that picture on his TikTok and someone in the comments of the TikTok said that his car had a question.

21:45.986 --> 21:47.046
What am I doing here?

21:47.066 --> 21:48.247
That's what it’s thinking.

21:48.967 --> 21:52.108
But I mean, finally, Aksoy, he got the start he needed.

21:52.608 --> 21:56.810
Controlled when he controlled the weight and Bansal was charging behind him.

21:57.430 --> 22:02.632
And I think ultimately Bansal was probably a bit faster, but actually managed to hold him off.

22:03.402 --> 22:14.526
I mean, Aksoy and Bansal is maybe not like the rivalry we would have expected, but if it comes down to more races between the two of them, I would be super happy.

22:14.546 --> 22:23.449
And I think it was great to see how mature they also performed because I know quite a few of the drivers with the speed that they had going on.

22:23.469 --> 22:27.190
And also, I mean, especially Aksoy is so early in his career.

22:27.857 --> 22:36.099
Yeah, because Bansal, of course, he is the GB4 champion, so he does have that experience, but I'm so excited to come in.

22:36.739 --> 22:39.079
And it was a tricky condition as well, of course.

22:39.240 --> 22:43.060
It was a bit of a light rain, but they were all on slicks, so it was difficult to manage.

22:43.380 --> 22:51.002
Meanwhile, we had Bondarev, who was, I mean, he was clearly struggling for pace, I mean, you could see a bit of a train forming behind him.

22:51.342 --> 22:54.783
He had like a three second gap between him and the next car ahead of him, and

22:55.163 --> 23:00.390
Cars were slowly overtaking him but he clearly did not have the pace along with Cosma.

23:00.601 --> 23:15.716
To throw in the second, when we talk about Bansal and GB4, I think we need to address the fact that GB4 is miles away from Italian F4, from the cars, from how the racing works, it's totally different.

23:15.816 --> 23:24.865
And I know a lot of people were unsure if Bansal is really that crazy good because GB4 is famously not one of the most competitive.

23:25.515 --> 23:37.961
I think for me, for Bansal his performance in FWS kind of very much showed that he should be able to because I mean being secon–He was third– I mean he should have been second to DVL I mean.

23:38.681 --> 23:52.227
I always supported him but my point is also that I think on the other hand the experience coming from Great Britain where these you know bit of wet races are more likely I think that definitely helped them a bit though.

23:53.059 --> 24:01.304
Yeah, but I mean, he was so much hound, I mean, the gap was very much around kind of hovering around 5 to 3 tenths, so I'd say for most of the race, but...

24:01.985 --> 24:02.605
It was really good.

24:02.865 --> 24:14.313
Yeah, and again, when Costoya and Craigie both making a lot of positions, Craigie started in P24, Costoya in P26 in their recovery, P13 and P15 in the end, so...

24:15.101 --> 24:16.822
But Consani also made a decent recovery.

24:16.862 --> 24:20.585
He started at P14 and ended up was at P7.

24:21.045 --> 24:25.768
For Costoya and I mean for Craigie and Consani, it’s keeping a clean weekend.

24:26.348 --> 24:31.411
And Costoya, is just getting a better qualifying, which will come with experience.

24:31.471 --> 24:34.734
And again, David Walther on the podium.

24:35.254 --> 24:41.038
We had a real underdog podium, I felt like, because it was all drivers, people don't really keep an eye on.

24:41.298 --> 24:42.138
But I think it's great.

24:42.318 --> 24:42.959
I think it's beautiful.

24:43.437 --> 24:51.026
See then, all of this, Aksoy actually taking two wins and three podiums, who's the only driver to finish on the podium all three races.

24:51.767 --> 24:58.294
He ends up being the championship leader on 82 points, which going into this, I don't think anybody expected.

24:58.314 --> 25:02.900
I mean, it is a Prema-dominated top three, just not the three we expected.

25:03.795 --> 25:08.059
moving on too fast for me because I still wanted to mention about the fourth race.

25:08.980 --> 25:29.278
I was really really disappointed that Emma Felbermayr couldn't start the race because she had to stay in the pit lane because her car had some sort of issue and generally I wanted to point out that she had an incredibly unlucky weekend but the seconds where she was not unlucky it was really really

25:30.618 --> 25:34.399
great for her because we saw her run in top 10 at points.

25:35.519 --> 25:44.602
Her qualifying was interrupted, she had the problem with the car, she had, you know, the grid penalty from putting the car on too early.

25:44.822 --> 25:54.224
A lot of bad luck came together but I think it was really promising how she still managed to deliver and I think it's really promising for the next few weekends.

25:54.900 --> 26:04.023
The championship standings look kind of crazy to me, because the two guys who people assumed would be fighting for the title are in P6 and P10.

26:04.623 --> 26:23.110
Yeah, so Aksoy, he has a decent lead, I mean, he has 16 point lead, he’s on a 3 point with Maccagnani on 66 points here in P2, Cosma in third on 61, Bansal fourth with 60, and Walther in the fifth with 58 points here.

26:23.690 --> 26:25.071
quite a hoard of points for him.

26:25.672 --> 26:29.214
P2 to P6 are all really close to each other in points.

26:29.955 --> 26:32.997
Like, there's 12 points separating those 5 drivers.

26:34.913 --> 26:47.404
Yeah, and I mean, even between like, I mean, P6 Bondarev, only 4 points behind Walther, so I mean, he just needs to have a good weekend and he can recover that kind of deficit he has to Aksoy.

26:48.104 --> 26:55.491
And I mean, in the teams yet, you know, surprise, surprise, Prema leading, I mean, I don't think anybody is surprised by that.

26:56.656 --> 27:16.459
I mean, I could, I would have imagined US racing to be closer in points because like Prema’s at 160, US is at 126, but I think, majority of the fact that they're so far behind is because Sammalisto, the car just broke down and right.

27:16.479 --> 27:25.941
I mean, if it wasn't for that, I think if I do the rough calculations, I think they should only be separated by a very few points.

27:27.196 --> 27:31.777
R-ace is P7 in the championship and it really hurts.

27:32.897 --> 27:36.298
I think it's crazy that Maffi Racing is P4.

27:36.318 --> 27:38.999
That's actually insane.

27:39.759 --> 27:42.700
It'd be even more insane if they could keep up the rest of the season.

27:43.280 --> 27:47.841
If we see a Maffi car win, I'm going to cry.

27:48.221 --> 27:56.203
But out of happiness because I'd be so happy for the drivers who are able to do it even with a car that should be a**.

27:56.791 --> 27:58.932
Hey, you should dye your hair like the team colours

27:59.332 --> 28:00.192
What's the team colours?

28:00.552 --> 28:02.112
I don't know, off the top of my head.

28:02.152 --> 28:02.712
Hang on.

28:02.972 --> 28:04.073
Do you have any idea Robin?

28:04.493 --> 28:05.113
No idea.

28:05.253 --> 28:06.253
Wait, I'm looking it up.

28:06.933 --> 28:09.634
Unless it's blue or green.

28:10.754 --> 28:11.535
Blue and yellow.

28:11.555 --> 28:12.455
I would do yellow.

28:12.655 --> 28:13.255
I would do yellow.

28:13.595 --> 28:14.135
I would do it.

28:14.635 --> 28:15.756
Are you not blonde already?

28:16.216 --> 28:16.476
No.

28:16.896 --> 28:19.296
Currently my hair is like red, more.

28:20.077 --> 28:20.677
Oh, fair enough.

28:20.897 --> 28:22.377
Oh, that's actually such a nice livery.

28:22.877 --> 28:24.578
Like I've never seen it properly like still.

28:24.598 --> 28:25.798
That's actually quite cute.

28:26.322 --> 28:27.502
Okay, good, so we have a plan.

28:29.063 --> 28:31.683
Dying your hair if they get a win.

28:32.123 --> 28:33.104
I think it would be really fun.

28:33.464 --> 28:35.124
You guys heard it here first.

28:35.744 --> 28:43.306
Okay, so the next weekend is in Vallelunga in May 22nd to 24th.

28:44.286 --> 28:48.727
And it's going to be the same format with, like the two group qualifying on the four different races.

28:49.007 --> 28:51.488
Because again, we have too many drivers.

28:52.141 --> 28:58.725
Yeah, the maximum capacity of Vallelunga is 37 drivers, like Misano.

28:59.126 --> 29:04.289
So unless we end up losing like 10 drivers, it'll have to be Group quali.

29:04.830 --> 29:09.192
But we will definitely lose some drivers because not many, but like 3 or 4.

29:09.453 --> 29:20.080
I think 3 should be because it overlaps with F1 Academy, so Emma, Rafa and Payton definitely will not be there.

29:20.471 --> 29:22.474
Yeah, but I don't think we're getting that to a grid of 37.

29:22.635 --> 29:26.341
I mean, maybe we still lose a few more drivers.

29:26.641 --> 29:27.022
Who knows?

29:27.042 --> 29:29.586
I mean, who knows if Prema will even exist.

29:29.947 --> 29:30.187
So.

29:30.970 --> 29:36.312
Yeah, and I think in terms of next round, I do think Bondarev will improve.

29:36.732 --> 29:53.759
I mean, he was able to improve a lot from last year, so I would expect him to improve, and I do want to see Aksoy keep this up, but I'm not too sure if he can, but I would love to see him be able to, because it's really nice to be able to see him do well.

29:53.779 --> 29:56.620
I want to go back to the quality format thing real quick.

29:57.701 --> 30:04.607
Hopefully, we should be doing the normal three race weekend in Monza because the circuit capacity is 49.

30:04.927 --> 30:11.313
So unless we get a bigger grid than we have right now, we should be set for a normal race weekend in Monza.

30:11.873 --> 30:16.978
No, I think we should do four races simply because I want more races at Monza.

30:17.318 --> 30:19.600
Mr Monzabanking starts again.

30:20.485 --> 30:30.629
And possibly if we lose a couple more drivers, we could have the normal race weekend in Mugello, because the circuit capacity there is 46.

30:30.689 --> 30:33.851
So maybe we'll have normal race weekends.

30:33.891 --> 30:34.371
Who knows?

30:34.391 --> 30:37.012
No, I think we should have four races at Monza.

30:37.512 --> 30:38.773
Of course you do.

30:38.953 --> 30:41.434
We should just do a fourth race at Monza, because it's fun.

30:41.834 --> 30:42.855
Have we considered that?

30:43.695 --> 30:44.335
Just for fun.

30:44.536 --> 30:46.316
Bring back the old layout for one race.

30:47.017 --> 30:47.897
Just with the banking?

30:48.077 --> 30:50.058
Oh, send the kids up the banking.

30:50.502 --> 30:50.842
Yes.

30:51.482 --> 30:55.744
Whoever finishes a lap without crashing gets 100 points.

30:56.364 --> 30:57.284
Makes sense, yeah.

30:57.924 --> 30:59.465
Yeah, you know that's how it works.

31:00.225 --> 31:10.508
But yeah, in terms of upcoming rounds, like I said, looks positive for R-ace, hopefully the drivers can lock in a bit and stop getting penalties.

31:11.282 --> 31:23.448
I think Bansal will get past Cosma at the very least in the championship because I think he will still improve the slightest bit and we will see him win very very soon.

31:23.807 --> 31:24.608
Yeah, I can see that.

31:25.188 --> 31:25.889
Niamh, what about you?

31:25.949 --> 31:26.590
What do you think?

31:27.250 --> 31:28.531
I'm scared of jinxing people.

31:28.832 --> 31:32.995
Like, I don't believe, I'm not a particularly superstitious person.

31:33.496 --> 31:36.899
However, I do believe in, like, jinxes.

31:37.780 --> 31:41.283
So I really hope that Emily Cotty can keep getting

31:41.903 --> 31:57.371
You know, it was like P15s even like obviously she was running in P13, Emma was apparently running in P10 at one point Like I really hope we see more of that from the girls because I think it's actually a really really strong field of female drivers in Italian F4 at the moment

31:58.912 --> 32:16.225
I wouldn't say luckily Vallelunga is the only weekend that overlaps with F1 Academy officially so I think we should see definitely Emma do all the other races and hopefully Rafa maybe we will see more and obviously Peyton and

32:16.825 --> 32:22.170
Hopefully we will see more from Academy drivers, you know, just do like enough weekend and I think they should all do Monza.

32:22.791 --> 32:26.754
Anyways, the point is, I think we saw it with Emma.

32:27.375 --> 32:39.105
I'm a bit sad that she will miss the next round, but I think she will definitely score points in, definitely also score good points, maybe even top 10s in the long runs of the championship.

32:39.673 --> 32:47.235
Um, Payton has been confirmed to be doing six rounds of Italian F4, and I'm pretty sure the season is seven rounds.

32:47.775 --> 32:49.936
So she'll be doing everything but Vallelunga.

32:50.736 --> 32:51.656
Yeah, that's what I mean.

32:51.716 --> 32:56.517
I just forgot about her for a second because, uh, I forgot she's doing F1 Academy.

32:56.838 --> 33:01.059
She's also doing one round of Euro4... Why is she only doing one round?

33:01.739 --> 33:02.139
No idea.

33:02.670 --> 33:04.833
Wait, why is she not doing all of them?

33:05.514 --> 33:07.918
Do any of them overlap with F1 Academy?

33:08.239 --> 33:12.906
I mean, to be fair, there are  only three rounds of Euro4, so maybe the other two just overlap.

33:13.166 --> 33:15.029
Yeah, at that point just do all three.

33:15.309 --> 33:17.553
But maybe they overlap with F1 Academy.

33:18.462 --> 33:24.790
I just remembered, I swear to God, I saw that Mathilda Racing was testing some Italian circuits.

33:25.351 --> 33:30.137
So I hope we will see Jade Jacquet and Mathilda Paatz also.

33:30.718 --> 33:33.341
Hopefully Italian F4, potentially Euro4.

33:33.702 --> 33:35.945
Anyways, we need to get on, British F4.

33:36.265 --> 33:42.590
The races this weekend were really, really good, especially Race 3, but let's not get into Race 3 yet.

33:43.091 --> 33:44.832
Let's go through the first two races first.

33:45.293 --> 33:51.698
I mean, in qualifying, there's a bit of a shock with Dries van Langendonck only qualifying down in P8.

33:51.918 --> 33:53.199
He wanted to test himself.

33:53.580 --> 33:54.801
We thought he was washed.

33:55.481 --> 33:57.463
No, I just don't want to test himself.

33:58.003 --> 34:02.347
You know, he has to prove that he can also do well when he's not starting from pole.

34:03.195 --> 34:13.986
The first two were in Race 1, I mean, Al Azhari was on pole but Jeff-Hall took the lead from off the start, DVL only really made one move onto P7 and he just kind of stayed there the whole race.

34:14.427 --> 34:15.388
He didn't really, I mean.

34:15.946 --> 34:18.488
It was like I've had enough of being good guys, I'm just going to sit here.

34:18.508 --> 34:26.273
Yeah, and I mean, again, finally, it's nice to see Harfield up at the front because we saw last time out of Donington Park,

34:26.573 --> 34:37.881
he was fast, but he got a bit unlucky in qualifying, so I mean, he made it up to third at the start, nearly made it into second, but then I think, I mean, I think I enjoy the Donington Park races more.

34:38.601 --> 34:45.286
It seems like overall, they’re struggling to overtake at Brands Hatch, which is my impression, but that's what it seems like.

34:45.766 --> 34:47.889
Jeff-Hall has been really impressing me.

34:48.250 --> 34:56.682
I mean, he was in the championship lead for a bit and like, I think over the course of the season, he could possibly challenge DVL for the title.

34:57.143 --> 35:01.129
He is a Ginetta Junior Champion and a Mercedes junior, I mean.

35:01.447 --> 35:14.077
I wanted to mention, I also prefer Donnington, but I just prefer the track generally because Brands Hatch is, I think at the very least it looks more tight, so that was a bit safe thought on the start.

35:14.357 --> 35:19.001
When faster drivers struggled to get further in front, there was no space.

35:19.503 --> 35:24.268
Yeah, I mean, you could see most of the moves made were basically on start and restarts.

35:24.628 --> 35:27.551
Other than that, it felt like there was not that much overtaking.

35:27.611 --> 35:31.335
I mean, how will you have space to overtake if there is no space?

35:31.795 --> 35:33.196
And it's such a small track as well.

35:33.216 --> 35:36.039
I mean, it's the shortest track on the calendar, I think.

35:36.460 --> 35:38.802
I mean, lap times were like, what, 45 seconds?

35:39.247 --> 35:45.191
Yeah so there's also obviously not a lot of corners or anything where you could plan to overtake.

35:45.711 --> 35:55.417
But like, in true F4 fashion we had two safety cars and even a red flag because it's- It’s not F4 without safety cars.

35:55.877 --> 35:58.419
I mean Race 2 again, you’ve got DVL, I mean.

35:58.739 --> 36:03.422
He had a good start until Joseph Smith pushed him right onto the grass.

36:04.104 --> 36:22.266
I think his start was too good almost, because it's exactly what I just said in which he looked way faster than the guys next and in front of him, but there was no space, like he looked fully get into it but there was no space to go, so he got pushed because of that, kind of. 

36:22.266 --> 36:28.489
If he was more at the speed of the others, I don't think that would have happened, but also then he wouldn't be DVL.

36:29.636 --> 36:41.079
Yeah, and I think he had a better pace this week, because of course, Jeff-Hall, who did win race 1, finishing right behind him, but he then eventually dropped and DVL ended up losing another position.

36:41.539 --> 36:51.101
And I mean, yeah, I mean, Joseph Smith did end up getting karma, because he got a 5-second penalty, for track limits, not for pushing DVL wide, but still karma, I'm gonna say.

36:51.481 --> 36:59.363
And again, Harfield impressing, making up three positions, which I mean, given how tight it was on this track, is again quite impressive.

36:59.783 --> 37:01.683
I think I need to be a bit mean here.

37:01.743 --> 37:06.304
A driver that did not impress me was Alfie Slater, who...

37:06.324 --> 37:07.884
I think he cooked his tires.

37:08.445 --> 37:10.465
P11 to P16 in one lap.

37:10.945 --> 37:18.726
It's just, you know, I was also a bit sorry for him because I felt that the commentators were really focused on him and they wanted him to do well.

37:18.746 --> 37:21.447
And they're like, oh my god, he could get his first points here.

37:21.787 --> 37:24.507
And like, in that lap, he just dropped down.

37:24.547 --> 37:26.008
It was, it was sad.

37:26.508 --> 37:27.348
I was sorry for him.

37:27.760 --> 37:32.123
I think it's, I mean, yeah, you could see, I think he just overcooked his tyres, in the moment they went off.

37:32.203 --> 37:34.444
He had everybody and he went a bit wide.

37:34.464 --> 37:36.285
That gave space to everyone and they all just like.

37:36.306 --> 37:49.554
But he's also in a Rodin and like he should, he should be higher up there and like, closer to the likes of Lennon and Van Langendock.

37:50.116 --> 37:57.262
I mean, to be fair, I mean, with Lennon, even though he's not necessarily got the results in the races, he's still been qualifying a lot better.

37:57.683 --> 37:58.664
Yes, what I mean, like...

37:59.084 --> 38:07.692
It's two weekends in a row now, but... Yeah, also, I want to shout out Scott Lindblom, because, again, I really enjoyed his race craft.

38:08.212 --> 38:10.875
I've been saying this quite a while about him.

38:11.395 --> 38:17.861
I think he has excellent racecraft and he just has the ability to make those moves at the right time, there's overtakes.

38:17.881 --> 38:25.688
Because he's one of the few drivers who made a few overtakes during the race, which again, as was mentioned, it was extremely hard to overtake it seems like.

38:26.930 --> 38:27.810
I absolutely agree.

38:27.890 --> 38:32.575
I do really, really think that he's got really, really nice racecraft.

38:32.595 --> 38:33.316
Like it was obvious.

38:33.896 --> 38:39.102
I can't even remember what championship it was he did over the winter, but I remember watching it and just thinking, oh, it's good.

38:39.562 --> 38:40.263
UAE4.

38:40.523 --> 38:41.284
UAE4.

38:41.505 --> 38:43.447
I was gonna say that, but I didn't want to be wrong.

38:44.788 --> 38:46.890
But yeah, I remember watching him then thinking, oh, that's good.

38:47.231 --> 38:50.494
Just as long as he keeps it, and clearly he has if he's bringing it into this championship.

38:50.715 --> 38:52.537
Like, I just think he's a really good driver.

38:52.898 --> 39:06.146
I wish he'd also keep it clearly in the qualifying, because I feel like he should be really up there every single time, but for some reason, there's always some problem that keeps him from being where he should be.

39:06.606 --> 39:15.271
But hopefully, you know, we know he has the talent, it's just about getting the qualifying sorted, but I think we will see more and more of him as the rounds go on.

39:15.811 --> 39:21.495
But then, I mean, compared to the first two races tho, race three was a proper cracker, that was so much fun.

39:22.152 --> 39:24.413
Race 3 felt like a fever dream.

39:24.433 --> 39:26.374
What was going on?

39:26.794 --> 39:33.237
Like, before the race even started, you had like half the grid in the pit lane because they were changing from wets to slicks.

39:33.998 --> 39:41.741
If you're going to declare it’s a wet race, you'll have wets on, but I think on the formation lap, some drivers realise, oh, it's actually feeling pretty dry.

39:41.761 --> 39:42.742
I can go on slicks.

39:43.562 --> 39:47.325
And of course, when you're at the back, it's like you have nothing to lose.

39:47.805 --> 39:52.248
If you're down in like P25, you have nothing to lose, you might as well go for it.

39:52.368 --> 39:58.292
But notably, one of the drivers who went for the slicks was none other than Dries Van Langendock.

39:58.972 --> 40:02.815
I think, what was it that caused the safety car in the beginning?

40:02.835 --> 40:07.558
Somebody spinning out, or something I don't fully remember.

40:08.038 --> 40:12.001
I don't remember what caused the safety car, but the safety car caught the wrong driver.

40:12.980 --> 40:14.100
And it was really funny.

40:14.120 --> 40:22.843
I think there's quite a big gap because you had, I think, you had all the slick tyre one and there's a gap between the wet tyre runners and the slick tyre runners.

40:23.363 --> 40:31.086
But also, Brands Hatch is just so small that it was really difficult because they were separated all over the circuit.

40:31.106 --> 40:38.588
It was difficult to figure out where the start is and where the last cars are, because it was just all separated.

40:38.950 --> 40:43.295
So the safety car ended up picking up Chiara Battig, who was in P14.

40:45.602 --> 40:47.183
instead of the actual race leader.

40:47.703 --> 40:57.506
And then after the safety car period was over, they just had all the drivers go past the safety car until it finally picked up Al Azhari again.

40:58.506 --> 41:12.750
It was really funny, because I think the commentators were saying that it was possible for them to red flag the session, but then that would have really ruined the race for anyone who took the gamble to go on slicks in the beginning.

41:13.648 --> 41:15.388
It's just the most F4 race ever.

41:15.408 --> 41:20.270
I mean, it's not F4 with a bit of chaos and a bit of everything.

41:20.790 --> 41:39.814
But it was really interesting to see, you know, how the different drivers worked on the different tires because you could see that it was really, in between if the slicks were really good idea or if, you know, it was maybe a bit too wet to do that.

41:40.234 --> 41:42.495
But I mean, DVL was insane.

41:43.140 --> 41:48.327
It really looked like he was playing one of the F1 games on like zero AI.

41:48.347 --> 41:51.933
He was just like, how many overtakes did he make in one lap?

41:51.953 --> 41:58.081
He was like getting past one person and then immediately catching up to the next person and overtaking them as well.

41:58.602 --> 41:59.443
It was insane.

42:00.144 --> 42:06.350
I mean, of course yes it's on tyre strategy, but he only had to over-, I mean there were drivers ahead of him also on slicks, he only had to get up-

42:07.011 --> 42:14.899
It reminded me very much of Freddie Slater’s win at Spa last year, when he started down in P23, took the gamble on tyres.

42:15.499 --> 42:24.288
It's very much the same thing, well of course you know it's a tyre strategy win but he had to get ahead of all the drivers, he had to have the skill and he ended up winning by like four seconds.

42:24.858 --> 42:26.902
I was also really impressed by Harfield.

42:27.864 --> 42:35.197
He was running on slicks, broke his front wing, came into the pits to change it, and then still ended up what, P5?

42:35.217 --> 42:36.159
Fifth.

42:37.075 --> 42:41.698
